NOW women can buy punani panties &ndash; and many men are angry about it!But shopkeepers are smiling, saying the fake punani panties are flying off the shelves.Jeremiah Ndaba (34) told Daily Sun it is a turn-off when he gets to bed and finds he has been deceived by a fake punani.&ldquo;I think it is wrong to put on the panties and cheat men by pretending they are something they are not,&rdquo; he said.&ldquo;I&rsquo;d rather want her to get dressed and leave my place.&rdquo;A woman buying the panties said it gives her confidence when she walks around, especially when she is wearing tight pants. &ldquo;I love it. It doesn&rsquo;t take long before men start asking for cellphone numbers,&rdquo; she said.She said men tell her they love this kind of punani and want their wives to be like her. &ldquo;I have a boyfriend and he doesn&rsquo;t mind. He buys me tight trousers that make him proud when we go out,&rdquo; she said.Selina Mathola said she feels complete with the punani panties. &ldquo;I know it is not what I really am but at least men love what they see.&rdquo; Selina said as a young woman she wants to be admired when she walks around the mall.&ldquo;The punani panties are the way to do it,&rdquo; she said.Shop owner Syaid Moffat said women, especially skinny ones, flock to his shop to buy the panties. &ldquo;The demand is high and I sometimes run out of stock,&rdquo; he said. But he said his customers don&rsquo;t openly buy the panties.&ldquo;They try to hide from other customers,&rdquo; he said.